# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: yne
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:yne/al] In chemistry, the suffix **-al** is the IUPAC nomenclature used in organic chemistry to form names of aldehydes containing the -(CO)H group in the systematic form.
[src:yne/al] It was extracted from the word "aldehyde".
[src:yne/al] With the exception of chemical compounds having a higher priority than it, all aldehydes are named using -al, such as 'propanal'.
[src:yne/al] Some aldehydes also have common names, such as formaldehyde for methanal, acetaldehyde for ethanal.
[src:yne/al] Benzaldehyde does not have a systematic form with -al.
[src:yne/ane] In organic chemistry, the suffix ***-ane*** forms the names of organic compounds where the −C−C− group (a carbon-carbon single bond) has been attributed the highest priority according to the rules of organic nomenclature.
[src:yne/ane] Such organic compounds are called *alkanes*.
[src:yne/ane] The names of the saturated hydrides of non-metals end with the suffix ***-ane***: the hydrides of silicon are called silanes (SiH4); the hydrides of boron are boranes (B2H6).
[src:yne/ane] The final "*-e*" is dropped before a suffix that starts with a vowel, e.g.
[src:yne/ane] Alternatively, "*-ane*" may be used for a mononuclear hydride of an element.
[src:yne/ane] For instance, methane for CH4 and oxidane for H2O (water).
[src:yne/ase] The suffix **-ase** is used in biochemistry to form names of enzymes.
[src:yne/ase] The most common way to name enzymes is to add this suffix onto the end of the substrate, *e.g.* an enzyme that breaks down peroxides may be called peroxidase; the enzyme that produces telomeres is called telomerase.
[src:yne/ase] Sometimes enzymes are named for the function they perform, rather than substrate, e.g. the enzyme that polymerizes (assembles) DNA into strands is called polymerase; see also reverse transcriptase.
[src:yne/ase] The *-ase* suffix is a libfix derived from "diastase", the first recognized enzyme.
[src:yne/ase] Its usage in subsequently discovered enzymes was proposed by Émile Duclaux, with the intention of honoring the first scientists to isolate diastase.
[src:yne/ene] The suffix **-ene** is used in organic chemistry to form names of organic compounds where the -C=C- group has been attributed the highest priority according to the rules of organic nomenclature.
[src:yne/ene] Sometimes a number between hyphens is inserted before it to say that the double bond is between that atom and the atom with the next number up.
[src:yne/ene] This suffix is taken from the end of the word ethylene, which is the simplest alkene.
[src:yne/ene] The final "-e" disappears if it is followed by a suffix that starts with a vowel, e.g.
[src:yne/ene] "-enal" which is a compound that contains both a -C=C- bond and an aldehyde functional group.
[src:yne/ene] A Greek number prefix before the "-ene" indicates how many double bonds there are in the compound, e.g. butadiene.
[src:yne/ene] The suffix "-ene" is also used in inorganic chemistry to indicate a one-atom thick two-dimensional layer of atoms—known as a "Xene"—as in graphene, silicene, stanene, borophene, and germanene.
[src:yne/ene] Additionally, the suffixis used for MXenes due to their similarity to graphene.
[src:yne/ine] *asinine, canine, feline, ursine*), the suffix is usually pronounced /aɪn/ or in some words alternatively /ɪn/.
[src:yne/ine] *Levantine, Byzantine, Argentine*) it is usually /aɪn/ or /iːn/.
[src:yne/ine] But in chemistry, it is usually pronounced /iːn/ or /ɪn/ depending on the word it appears in and the accent of the speaker.
[src:yne/ine] In a few words (for example, *quinine*, *iodine* and *strychnine*), the /aɪn/ sound is normal in some accents.
[src:yne/ine] *Gasoline* ends with /iːn/; *glycerine* more often with /ɪn/ than with /iːn/.
[src:yne/ine] In *caffeine*, the suffix has merged with the *e* in the root, for stressed /ˈiːn/; in *gasoline* and *margarine* as well the suffix is stressed by some people.
[src:yne/ine] Some elements of the periodic table (namely the halogens, in the Group 17) have this suffix: fluorine (F), chlorine (Cl), bromine (Br), iodine (I) and astatine (At), ending which was continued in the artificially created tennessine (Ts).
[src:yne/ine] The suffix *-in* (/ɪn/) is etymologically related and overlaps in usage with *-ine*.
[src:yne/ine] Many proteins and lipids have names ending with *-in*: for example, the enzymes pepsin and trypsin, the hormones insulin and gastrin, and the lipids stearin (stearine) and olein.
[src:yne/oate] The suffix **-oate** is the IUPAC nomenclature used in organic chemistry to form names of compounds formed with ester.
[src:yne/oate] The most common examples of compounds named with the "oate" suffix are esters, like ethyl acetate, CH 3COOCH 2CH 3.
[src:yne/oic-acid] In organic chemistry, a **carboxylic acid** is a polar, organic acid that contains a **carboxyl group** (−C(=O)−OH) attached to an R-group.
[src:yne/oic-acid] The general formula of a carboxylic acid is often written as **R−COOH** or **R−CO2H**, sometimes as R−C(O)OH, with R referring to an organyl group (e.g., alkyl, alkenyl, aryl), or hydrogen, or other groups.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Important examples include the amino acids and fatty acids.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Deprotonation of a carboxylic acid gives a carboxylate anion.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Carboxylic acids are often considered weak acids as they only partially ionise (dissociate) in water.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Carboxylic acids are commonly identified by their trivial names.
[src:yne/oic-acid] IUPAC-recommended names also exist; in this system, carboxylic acids have an *-oic acid* suffix.
[src:yne/oic-acid] For example, butyric acid (CH3CH2CH2CO2H) is butanoic acid by IUPAC guidelines.
[src:yne/oic-acid] For nomenclature of complex molecules containing a carboxylic acid, the carboxyl can be considered position one of the parent chain even if there are other substituents, such as 3-chloropropanoic acid.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Alternately, it can be named as a "carboxy" or "carboxylic acid" substituent on another parent structure, such as 2-carboxyfuran.
[src:yne/oic-acid] The carboxylate anion (R−COO− or R−CO−2) of a carboxylic acid is usually named with the suffix *-ate*, in keeping with the general pattern of *-ic acid* and *-ate* for a conjugate acid and its conjugate base, respectively.
[src:yne/oic-acid] For example, the conjugate base of acetic acid is acetate.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Carbonic acid, which occurs in bicarbonate buffer systems in nature, is not generally classed as one of the carboxylic acids, despite it having a moiety that looks like a COOH group.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Because they are both hydrogen-bond acceptors (the carbonyl −C(=O)−) and hydrogen-bond donors (the hydroxyl −OH), they also participate in hydrogen bonding.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Together, the hydroxyl and carbonyl group form the functional group carboxyl.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Carboxylic acids usually exist as dimers in nonpolar media due to their tendency to "self-associate".
[src:yne/oic-acid] Smaller carboxylic acids (1 to 5 carbons) are soluble in water, whereas bigger carboxylic acids have limited solubility due to the increasing hydrophobic nature of the alkyl chain.
[src:yne/oic-acid] These longer chain acids tend to be soluble in less-polar solvents such as ethers and alcohols.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Aqueous sodium hydroxide and carboxylic acids, even hydrophobic ones, react to yield water-soluble sodium salts.
[src:yne/oic-acid] For example, enanthic acid has a low solubility in water (0.2 g/L), but its sodium salt is very soluble in water.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Carboxylic acids tend to have higher boiling points than water, because of their greater surface areas and their tendency to form stabilized dimers through hydrogen bonds.
[src:yne/oic-acid] For boiling to occur, either the dimer bonds must be broken or the entire dimer arrangement must be vaporized, increasing the enthalpy of vaporization requirements significantly.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Carboxylic acids are Brønsted–Lowry acids because they are proton (H+) donors.
[src:yne/oic-acid] They are the most common type of organic acid.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Carboxylic acids are typically weak acids, meaning that they only partially dissociate into [H3O]+ cations and R−CO−2 anions in neutral aqueous solution.
[src:yne/oic-acid] For example, at room temperature, in a 1-molar solution of acetic acid, only 0.001% of the acid are dissociated (i.e.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Electron-withdrawing substituents such as trifluoromethyl (−CF3) give stronger acids (the p*K*a of acetic acid is 4.76 whereas trifluoroacetic acid, with a trifluoromethyl substituent, has a p*K*a of 0.23).
[src:yne/oic-acid] Deprotonation of carboxylic acids gives carboxylate anions; these are resonance stabilized, because the negative charge is delocalized over the two oxygen atoms, increasing the stability of the anion.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Each of the carbon–oxygen bonds in the carboxylate anion has a partial double-bond character.
[src:yne/oic-acid] The carbonyl carbon's partial positive charge is also weakened by the −1/2 negative charges on the 2 oxygen atoms.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Carboxylic acids often have strong sour odours.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Esters of carboxylic acids tend to have fruity, pleasant odours, and many are used in perfume.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Carboxylic acids are readily identified as such by infrared spectroscopy.
[src:yne/oic-acid] They exhibit a sharp band associated with vibration of the C=O carbonyl bond (*ν*C=O) between 1680 and 1725 cm−1.
[src:yne/oic-acid] A characteristic *ν*O–H band appears as a broad peak in the 2500 to 3000 cm−1 region.
[src:yne/oic-acid] By 1H NMR spectrometry, the hydroxyl hydrogen appears in the 10–13 ppm region, although it is often either broadened or not observed owing to exchange with traces of water.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Many carboxylic acids are produced industrially on a large scale.
[src:yne/oic-acid] They are also frequently found in nature.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Esters of fatty acids are the main components of lipids and polyamides of aminocarboxylic acids are the main components of proteins.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Carboxylic acids are used in the production of polymers, pharmaceuticals, solvents, and food additives.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Ribulose-1,5-bisphosphate carboxylase/oxygenase (aka RuBisCo), the most abundant protein, catalyzes the carbonation to give carboxylic acids.
[src:yne/oic-acid] This conversion is the carbon-fixation step in photosynthesis.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Routes to other biologically prevalent carboxylic acids - citric, oxalic, amino acids, etc. - entail hydrolysis of thioesters and phosphate esters.
[src:yne/oic-acid] In contrast to methods used on a laboratory scale, industrial routes to carboxylic acids often require specialized equipment for high pressures and high temperatures.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Preparative methods for small scale reactions for research or for production of fine chemicals often employ expensive consumable reagents.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Many reactions produce carboxylic acids but are used only in specific cases or are mainly of academic interest.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Carboxylic acids react with bases to form carboxylate salts, in which the hydrogen of the hydroxyl (–OH) group is replaced with a metal cation.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Widely practiced reactions convert carboxylic acids into esters, amides, carboxylate salts, acid chlorides, and alcohols.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Their conversion to esters is widely used, e.g. in the production of polyesters.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Likewise, carboxylic acids are converted into amides, but this conversion typically does not occur by direct reaction of the carboxylic acid and the amine.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Instead esters are typical precursors to amides.
[src:yne/oic-acid] The conversion of amino acids into peptides is a significant biochemical process that requires ATP.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Converting a carboxylic acid to an amide is possible, but not straightforward.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Instead of acting as a nucleophile, an amine will react as a base in the presence of a carboxylic acid to give the ammonium carboxylate salt.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Heating the salt to above 100 °C will drive off water and lead to the formation of the amide.
[src:yne/oic-acid] This method of synthesizing amides is industrially important, and has laboratory applications as well.
[src:yne/oic-acid] In the presence of a strong acid catalyst, carboxylic acids can condense to form acid anhydrides.
[src:yne/oic-acid] The condensation produces water, however, which can hydrolyze the anhydride back to the starting carboxylic acids.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Thus, the formation of the anhydride via condensation is an equilibrium process.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Under acid-catalyzed conditions, carboxylic acids will react with alcohols to form esters via the Fischer esterification reaction, which is also an equilibrium process.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Alternatively, diazomethane can be used to convert an acid to an ester.
[src:yne/oic-acid] While esterification reactions with diazomethane often give quantitative yields, diazomethane is only useful for forming methyl esters.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Like esters, most carboxylic acids can be reduced to alcohols by hydrogenation, or using hydride transferring agents such as lithium aluminium hydride.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Strong alkyl transferring agents, such as organolithium compounds but not Grignard reagents, will reduce carboxylic acids to ketones along with transfer of the alkyl group.
[src:yne/oic-acid] The Vilsmaier reagent (*N*,*N*-Dimethyl(chloromethylene)ammonium chloride; [ClHC=N+(CH3)2]Cl−) is a highly chemoselective agent for carboxylic acid reduction.
[src:yne/oic-acid] It selectively activates the carboxylic acid to give the carboxymethyleneammonium salt, which can be reduced by a mild reductant like lithium tris(*t*-butoxy)aluminum hydride to afford an aldehyde in a one pot procedure.
[src:yne/oic-acid] This procedure is known to tolerate reactive carbonyl functionalities such as ketone as well as moderately reactive ester, olefin, nitrile, and halide moieties.
[src:yne/oic-acid] The hydroxyl group on carboxylic acids may be replaced with a chlorine atom using thionyl chloride to give acyl chlorides.
[src:yne/oic-acid] In nature, carboxylic acids are converted to thioesters.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Thionyl chloride can be used to convert carboxylic acids to their corresponding acyl chlorides.
[src:yne/oic-acid] First, carboxylic acid **1** attacks thionyl chloride, and chloride ion leaves.
[src:yne/oic-acid] The resulting oxonium ion **2** is activated towards nucleophilic attack and has a good leaving group, setting it apart from a normal carboxylic acid.
[src:yne/oic-acid] In the next step, **2** is attacked by chloride ion to give tetrahedral intermediate **3**, a chlorosulfite.
[src:yne/oic-acid] The tetrahedral intermediate collapses with the loss of sulfur dioxide and chloride ion, giving protonated acyl chloride **4**.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Chloride ion can remove the proton on the carbonyl group, giving the acyl chloride **5** with a loss of HCl.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Phosphorus(III) chloride (PCl3) and phosphorus(V) chloride (PCl5) will also convert carboxylic acids to acid chlorides, by a similar mechanism.
[src:yne/oic-acid] One equivalent of PCl3 can react with three equivalents of acid, producing one equivalent of H3PO3, or phosphorus acid, in addition to the desired acid chloride.
[src:yne/oic-acid] PCl5 reacts with carboxylic acids in a 1:1 ratio, and produces phosphorus(V) oxychloride (POCl3) and hydrogen chloride (HCl) as byproducts.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Carboxylic acids react with Grignard reagents and organolithiums to form ketones.
[src:yne/oic-acid] The first equivalent of nucleophile acts as a base and deprotonates the acid.
[src:yne/oic-acid] A second equivalent will attack the carbonyl group to create a geminal alkoxide dianion, which is protonated upon workup to give the hydrate of a ketone.
[src:yne/oic-acid] Because most ketone hydrates are unstable relative to their corresponding ketones, the equilibrium between the two is shifted heavily in favor of the ketone.
[src:yne/oic-acid] For example, the equilibrium constant for the formation of acetone hydrate from acetone is only 0.002.
[src:yne/oic-acid] The carboxylic group is the most acidic in organic compounds.
[src:yne/oic-acid] The carboxyl radical, •COOH, only exists briefly.
[src:yne/oic-acid] The acid dissociation constant of •COOH has been measured using electron paramagnetic resonance spectroscopy.
[src:yne/oic-acid] The carboxyl group tends to dimerise to form oxalic acid.
[src:yne/yne] In chemistry, the suffix ***-yne*** is used to denote the presence of a triple bond (≡).
[src:yne/yne] The suffix follows IUPAC nomenclature, and is mainly used in organic chemistry.
[src:yne/yne] However, inorganic compounds featuring unsaturation in the form of triple bonds may be denoted by substitutive nomenclature with the same methods used with alkynes, i.e., the name of the corresponding saturated hydride is modified by replacing the "*-ane*" ending with "*-yne*".
[src:yne/yne] The suffix "*-diyne*" is used when there are two triple bonds, and so on.
[src:yne/yne] The position of unsaturation is indicated by a numerical locant immediately preceding the "*-yne*" suffix, or locants in the case of multiple triple bonds.
[src:yne/yne] Locants are chosen to be as low as possible.
[src:yne/yne] While generally used as a suffix, "*-yne*" is also used as an infix to name substituent groups that are triply bound to the parent compound.
[src:yne/yne] This suffix arose as a collapsed form of the end of the word *acetylene*.
[src:yne/yne] The final "*-e*" disappears if it is followed by another suffix that starts with a vowel.
